<TITLE> Job market must make more room for graduates: Iajuddin </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 15 (bdnews24.com)President Iajuddin Ahmed sounded a caution on Sunday that university graduates were not able to get satisfactory jobs due to the lack of suitable employment opportunities for them. The job market must be expanded to provide jobs for new graduates, so that the nation as a whole may be benefited by their education, talents and potential, he said, addressing the 12th convocation of Independent University, Bangladesh, as its chancellor. The IUB chancellor was troubled, however, that many private universities were failing to impart the desired level of education to their students. "We are keenly observing that the imparting of education being provided by many private universities could not reach up to the desired level," he said, The president also expressed concern that the high fees at private universities are prohibitive for poor but meritorious students. "In this connection, I urge the concerned authority to ventilate more opportunities for the meritorious but poor students in order to build a caring society," he said. Iajuddin called on all concerned to provide a congenial atmosphere to maintain the standard of education in private universities. The importance of quality education is of the essence for these times, Iajuddin said. He congratulated the graduating students on their achievement547 students received their degrees at the this year's IUB convocation, held at the Bangladesh-China Friendship Conference Centre. Education adviser Hossain Zillur Rahman attended the ceremony as special guest and Charles L Choguill, a professor of urban planning at King Saud University, Saudi Arabia, delivered the convocation address. bdmews
